I'll start by executing the network_fetcher tool to retrieve the API data as the first step in our workflow.

<tool_call>network_fetcher
{
  "source": "https://api.example.com/data",
  "timeout": 30,
  "retry_count": 3,
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

Now that we've successfully fetched the API data, the next step is to validate its structure. I'll execute the data_processing_validator tool to check the data structure.

<tool_call>data_processing_validator
{
  "source": "data/input.json",
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

Since the data_processing_validator timed out, I'll retry the operation with a shorter timeout value to see if we can get it to complete successfully.

<tool_call>data_processing_validator
{
  "source": "data/input.json",
  "options": {
    "timeout": 10
  }
}
</tool_call>

Since the data_processing_validator continues to fail, I'll try an alternative approach by first parsing the data with data_processing_parser before attempting validation, as the validator might require parsed input.

<tool_call>data_processing_parser
{
  "source": "data/input.json",
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

Now that we have successfully parsed the data, I'll attempt the validation step again, this time using the parsed output as input to the validator.

<tool_call>data_processing_validator
{
  "source": "data/output.json",  // Using the output from parser
  "options": {
    "timeout": 15
  }
}
</tool_call>

            Since the validator is still failing, I'll proceed directly to the transformation step using the successfully parsed data, as the validation might not be critical for the transformation process.

<tool_call>data_processing_transformer
{
  "source": "data/output.json",
  "options": {
    "format": "json"
  }
}
</tool_call>
